DATASET AND COMPUTE

- Intuitively felt that 147k samples was probably a LOT given the compute I had available (RTX 3050 mobile 4 gig/T4 on colab)
- Decided to limit to about 10,000 samples from the 147k, given the time constraint
- From the 10k samples, 8,737 were unique code strings whereas 2,333 were unique skeletons (stripped via regex)
- The repeatability explains the fast loss convergence (discussed further below)



MODEL ARCHITECTURE

- Decided to use CLIP to convert images into embeddings, and then feed them into a model
- To decide what model to use(was inclined towards GPT2), I first had to check how many tokens each sample had
- Tokenized the data using the GPT2 Tokenizer
- Evaluated distribution based on different percentiles
- Checked how many were above 950 (since GPT2 has a context window of 1024 tokens, and CLIP's embeddings amount to 50 tokens per image, (if all patch tokens are used, which was what i implemented for the finetuning))
- About 90% were below 950, so I collected data for only 10k samples with lengths below 950
- Asked claude for potential alternatives, it suggested Qwen 2.5
- Also tokenized using the Qwen's tokenizer - expected Qwen to compress the tokens but they didnt - increased them by 25%
- Printed a sample and found out that Qwen tokenizes each digit individually (i.e 54.43 -> 5 tokens whereas GPT2 treats the same input as 3 tokens)
-> This meant that Qwen could greatly benefit from rounding off digits as it would reduce the number of tokens required significantly (as the CadQuery dataset's code had numerical values with extremely long decimal places, for example: oop1=wp_sketch1.moveTo(0.1475328947368421, 0.0).lineTo(0.1475328947368421, 0.359375).lineTo(0.0, 0.359375).lineTo(0.0, 0.0).close())

- Selected CLIP + GPT2 with only the pooled CLIP embedding as baseline
- Originally wanted to train using LoRA, however Claude recommended that given GPT2 has never seen CadQuery and there is sufficient data, decided to implement full finetuning
- Finetune by giving all patch tokens CLIP embeddings instead of just the pooled one to build spatial awareness of the geometry
- Decided to pursue Qwen only if time permitted (tl;dr, it didnt :/ - but i will pursue this on my own time just so i can see what happens lol)


TRAINING

Ran on Colab free tier on the T4. 
Batch size 8, accumulated gradients 4 for run A.
Batch size 4, accumulated gradients 8 for run B. - this was because now I was passing 50 tokens for the image embedding instead of just 1, so memory was overflowing.

Since dataset was small, only ran for 2 epochs. Learning rate = 5e-5 (Claude recommended)

In full discretion, training code was assisted by claude, though I did make sure to write each line myself and made sure I understood what was happening.

